As far as immigration reform is concerned, I favor legalizing illigal immigrants who do not have significant criminal history (violent felonies) who have studied and/or worked in the US and their spouses and children.  The basis of this opinion is that the reality is that there are many people who are here illegally created by socio economic forces which the US and world economies contributed in creating.  Their labor helps the general public in keeping prices of fruits and vegetables and services low.  Legalization of illegal immigrants would allow them to receive more equitable salaries and not be subject to unfair treatment because of their immigration status.  Given that the US took land from Mexico much of what was American Southwest and given that most Americans came from ancestors who came here (with visa's or permission from Indian nations that existed here), I think it would not be morally wrong or out of place to grant liniency towards Mexican immigrants who are seeking similar opportunties.  /  / However, for practical reasons of needing to secure jobs for Americans who live in the US and to secure its borders, it is necessary to have immigration laws.  I would not be opposed to measures to restrict future immigration to the US, provided that US allows some immigration into the US at rates that its economy can absorb.  Nonetheless, unless the US is able to completely seal its borders, land and sea, and track visitors to the US, I do not see any practical means of preventing future illegal immigration.  The practical impact of legalizing illegal immigrants is that it may encourage others to come to the US.  However, for a Mexican who is coming to the US for work because his own village or city does not have jobs for him, he or she may not be so influenced by immigration policy as much as the immediate needs. /  / I don't think that there are any clear solutions to the immigration issues.  However, I am supportive of President Obama's policy of granting deferred action status to children of illegal immigrants and hope that he provides an avenue for legalization for such individuals.   /  / In establishing border control, I believe that the US should also take into account the human toll and impact of immigration policies to those who may be crossing the borders.  US should establish a policy which discourages illegal immigration without increasing danger or risk of life and limb to those who may cross the border out of desperation. /  / Finally, I would encourage US to support policies of decent and living wages and discourage exploitation of workers abroad by US companies.  To the extent workers have access to living wages or labor policies are more fair abroad, it would reduce the immigration pressures into the US.  /  /
